How can I quickly close a tab?
Pressing the hardware Back button is the fastest way. Flicking a tab onto the Close button is another good way.
I think pressing the Back button should minimize the browser!

Minimizing Brave when the hardware Back button is pressed is not feasible. Consider the following case:
1). example.com/page1 is loaded in the first tab.
2). You click a link on this page, and load example.com/page2 in the same tab.
3). You now want to go back to the link in step 1.

How do you do this if pressing the hardware Back button minimizes Brave? Pressing the tiny back indicator on the tab itself is not feasible.

Brave is a browser, and Android browsers have a long since established standard of either going back in the URL stack, or if no such stack exists, closing the current page when the Back button is pressed. Brave follows this standard.

There are 3 causes of this:
1). A browser other thank Brave is set as your default system browser. See the \"Set default system browser\" option in Brave\'s Settings to change this.
2). Brave has been configured not to intercept links from your current app. See the \"Intercept links from\" option in Brave\'s Settings.
3). Apps such as Talon, Reddit is Fun and others have inbuilt browsers that render links. Check the settings of that app and enable \"External browser\" or deselect \"Integrated browser\" or similar.

Note: other browser apps such as Chrome are hardcoded to load links in themselves, and thus Brave is unable to load links clicked from other browser apps.
How do I use Reading Mode? Why do some links not work?

Firstly, ensure Reading Mode is enabled (Settings -> App Controls / More… -> Reading Mode).

From that point, when Reading Mode is available for the current tab, the Reading Mode icon will display on the action bar (next to the Share button). Be aware that this icon only appears after the link has finished loading, and only if Brave successfully extracted content for Article Mode from the link.

Note: Extracting content from the web is an unreliable process, and may not work 100% accurately. Given the dynamic and ever-changing nature of the web itself, there is little than can be done here.
Will you add support for bookmarks, favorites, extensions, etc.?
Never say never, but for now Brave is focused solely on being the best possible way of loading and consuming links loaded from other apps.
Can I help translate the app?

I hope to add translation support soon.

When I do, I will definitely put a call out on Google+ (+Brave) for help with translations, so be sure to keep an eye on my feed.
Do you publish a feature roadmap? Can I up-vote upcoming features?
For competitive reasons, the answer to both of these questions is \'no\' I\'m afraid.

Brave only supports purchases via Google Play at this time.

Additional payment methods will hopefully be added in the future (assuming they do not violate the Google Play Developer Program Policies).
How do I type the name of the link I want to visit?
Just tap on the page / URL title. It will change to an edit control and provide suggestions based on your history and top sites.
Why can\'t I copy text from a web page?

Unfortunately Android system limitations prevent this from working.

Technical answer: Copy functionality works when using Android\'s WebView from an Activity, but not from a Service (which Brave uses).
Why doesn\'t the app draw over the translucent status bar?
Unfortunately Android system limitations prevent this.
Is there a beta programme? How can I join?
Details on the beta programme will be announced in due course. Keep an eye on my Google+ (+Brave) feed for announcements.
Why does Brave run slowly on my Nexus S / Galaxy S1 / Moto G class device?

Brave is a very resource intensive app, and consequently devices with lower specs can struggle to run the app as well as more powerful devices. Future updates will aim to improve Brave\'s performance, but there is only so much that can realistically be done here.

Technical answer: At the bare minimum, Brave requires the use of a Service and a WebView in order to function. Often multiple WebViews and even multiple Activities are also present. Naturally, allocating these items (especially the WebViews) consumes a lot of memory/resources. Lower spec devices generally have less memory available than Brave requires, and thus performance suffers as garbage collections are frequently triggered. As an example, the max heap size on the Nexus S is 48MB, compared to 192MB on the Nexus 5.
Sometimes web pages don\'t display correctly or videos don\'t play.

Brave uses the standard Android WebView, but unfortunately it is sometimes unreliable. Alternative web rendering methods such as FireFox\'s GeckoView and Chromium will likely be investigated going forward.

In the event a web page doesn\'t display correctly in Brave, the easiest thing to do is just to load a traditional browser for that link.
Why does the ongoing notification always display when Brave is running?
Unfortunately this ongoing notification is necessary to encourage the Android OS not to terminate Brave.
When is the next update coming?

When it\'s ready!

It\'s not feasible to be any more specific than that unfortunately (even to provide a ballpark estimate).

The reality is, when estimates are given people often end up taking them as a commitment, and can get upset if/when a release slips for whatever reason.
How can I quickly stop Brave from running?
Swipe from the top of the screen to open the notifications pane and click the \"Brave\" notification.
How can I remove Brave as the default browser?
System Settings -> Apps -> Downloaded -> Brave -> Clear defaults.
Question about the app? Try here.
By continuing, you acknowledge that you accept the Brave terms and privacy policy.
Brave is an all-new browser designed and crafted solely with mobile devices in mind.

Features include: • When you click on a link in an app, Brave loads that web page in the background, leaving you free to keep using your current app rather than your precious time being wasted watching a page load. Once the page has fully loaded, it will animate on screen. • Brave\'s flick physics allow you to go from clicking a link to sharing a link or adding it to a service such as Pocket in little more than a second! • Load multiple links from your current app at the same time. • Gracefully handles links that redirect to other apps. No longer does clicking an Instagram link in Twitter redirect to a full screen browser before loading Instagram! • Deep integration with the apps on your system. • Locates embedded YouTube videos on web pages, and provides a shortcut to load those videos directly in the YouTube app. • Handy stats that illustrate how much time you are saving by using Brave.

Regarding the Location permission: This is required so that you might grant permission for a website to access your location (such as those with an embedded map). Brave itself never accesses your location.
Click a link in an app.
A bubble will appear on the edge of the screen and the link will begin loading in the background. As soon as the page is loaded, it will be displayed.
It\'s that simple! With Brave, you can keep using your current app rather than wasting your time watching links redirect and waiting for pages to load. What\'s not to love about that?
